III Multimodal Visual Feature Fusion Based Channel Prediction Model
III-A Model Architecture
In this study, we propose a channel prediction framework for V2I communications based on multimodal visual feature fusion. By jointly leveraging semantic, depth-related, and geometric location information, the framework performs channel prediction through three key stages: multi-branch feature extraction, squeeze-and-excitation (SE)-attention-based gated fusion, and multilayer perceptron (MLP)-based regression, as shown in Fig. 1. Specifically, heterogeneous inputs are encoded into a unified latent space, adaptively fused, and then mapped to the target channel parameters.
1) Feature Extraction: The model employs a three-branch multimodal encoder to separately extract propagation-relevant features from each modality.
Semantic Feature Branch: A pretrained ResNet-34 backbone is adopted to encode semantic segmentation images resized to , where denotes the batch size. To improve training stability and reduce overfitting under limited data, the initial Conv, BatchNorm, and residual - are frozen, while only , , and a newly introduced feature mapping head are fine-tuned. Detailed network structures of residual block can be found in [28]. Specifically, the original classifier is replaced with an “fully connected (FC)ReLUDropout” module, which projects the 512-dimensional backbone output into a unified 256-dimensional semantic feature vector .
Depth Feature Branch: Depth images resized to are encoded by a lightweight convolutional neural network (CNN). Local spatial features are first extracted, then compressed by global average pooling (GAP), and finally projected through a FC layer into a unified 256-dimensional depth feature vector . This branch provides a low-cost global representation of the depth modality, complementing environment-related 3D structural cues for propagation characterization.
Location Feature Branch: To encode communication geometry, the longitude and latitude of Tx and Rx are first converted into a 1-dimensional (1D) geodetic distance, which is then fed into a two-layer MLP to generate a 256-dimensional location feature vector . In this way, location modality is projected into the same feature space as the semantic and depth branches for subsequent fusion.
2) Adaptive Feature Fusion Based on SE Attention: A gated SE attention module is introduced for adaptive multimodal fusion. Specifically, branch features are first concatenated along the channel dimension to form the fused representation , which is then globally pooled and passed through a lightweight gating network to generate attention weights . The fused features are subsequently rescaled by broadcast multiplication. Since , the proposed strategy performs sample-level gating, i.e., applying a shared scaling factor to each sample, thereby suppressing noisy or low-confidence samples and improving training stability and cross-scenario robustness.
3) Prediction Regression Head: An MLP is used to regress the fused features into scalar channel parameters, including PL, DS, ASA, and ASD, by progressively reducing the feature dimension and learning the nonlinear mapping from high-dimensional representations to propagation characteristics. Owing to the 360-dimensional normalized structure of APS, the regression head in Fig. 1 is not directly applicable, and a dedicated prediction architecture is presented separately in Section III-B.
III-B Prediction Head Design For APS Prediction
This module is redesigned from a single-output linear layer into a dedicated regression head for 360-dimensional (360D) APS prediction. As shown in Fig. 2, the fused features are first projected by an MLP with LayerNorm and a reduced dropout ratio into a 360D intermediate representation, where LayerNorm improves training stability and the lower dropout preserves fine-grained low-power details. To exploit the inherent 360∘ periodicity of APS, a 1D recurrent convolution module with CircularPad is further introduced, preserving the continuity between 0∘ and 359∘ while applying mild local smoothing. A residual fusion mechanism then combines raw features and smoothed features in a ratio of 0.2:0.8 to balance local detail preservation and global smoothness. Finally, a sigmoid activation constrains the output to , ensuring consistency with the normalized APS definition.
